===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{Han compound|艸|屯|日|ls=psc|t1=grass|t2=swollen sprout|t3=sun|c1=s|c2=p|c3=s|tr=*tʰun|tr2=*dˤun;*trun;*dun}}. Some oracle-bone and bronze forms contain only two components, either {{och-l|*艸}}/{{och-l|*屮}} with {{och-l|*屯}}, or {{och-l|*日}} with {{och-l|*屯}}.

The form {{och-l|*萅}} preserves the older arrangement with {{och-l|*艸}}. In the regular script, the {{och-l|*艸}} and {{och-l|*屯}} have merged into {{och-l|*𡗗}}.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|alt=萅,旾,㫩,𣇸,𣈤}}
{{etymid|zh|spring}}
{{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} relates it to {{och-l|芚|gloss=(of plants) to begin to grow}}; he also compares it {{cog|km|ដុះ||to grow; to germinate; to sprout}}, as well as {{och-l|穿|gloss=to bore through}} ([[ibid.]]).

{{zh-ref|Sagart (2023b)}} relates it to a vulgar (i.e. ignoble and popular) word which means "egg", which lacked a {{w|Chinese character|character}}, whose modern reflexes are {{w|Meixian dialect|Meixian}} {{cog|hak|春|tr=cun<sup>1</sup>|t=egg, roe}}, {{w|Sixian dialect|Sixian}} {{cog|hak|春|tr=chhûn}}, and {{cog|yue|春||egg, roe; testicle}} ({{w|IPA}}: {{IPAchar|/t͡ʃʰɵn⁵⁵/}}); and for which he further reconstructs {{cog|och|-}} ''*tʰu[n]'' ~ *''tʰu[r]''. He further relates OC ''*tʰu[n]'' ~ *''tʰu[r]'' to {{cog|brx|dəy}}, {{cog|lus|tui}}, {{cog|kar-pro|*ʔdejᴮ}}, from tentative {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*tur|*tʰur}}, (STEDT, however, reconstructs {{m|sit-pro|*tur|*d(w)əy|t=egg, testicle}}) and notes a connection between "eggs" and Chinese new year season, as birds generally nest and lay eggs in the warmer months in the north [https://www.skedaddlewildlife.com/location/durham-region/blog/when-do-birds-lay-eggs/].

